 This preserved repops and give the next raid a shot at a full plane.<br>
<br>
But now, the boss mobs are very hard.  Some have said you need to be 57+ to participate AND know the strategy.  Level 57 is above the average level for our planes raiders.  Thus, Cazic (and maybe Inny) are going to remain dormant for weeks if nobody is permitted to intervene between raids to kill him.  Cazic and his cousin would be unharvested and wasted.<br>
<br>
But some people are concerned that what SR did will lead to FFA, a degradation of the server, or a lack of respect of the rules.  They argue that the rules work fine now and that in a few months, more raids will be able to kill the boss.  They don't want interventions, they want people to be patient, even if that leads to waste.<br>
<br>
Most of SR is in their end game.  They have done pretty much what they can accomplish.  The sleepers tomb is left, plane of mischief, and some other places are left as well.  Cazic was something they could do.  They find having to wait weeks to do what they can do (and nobody else can do) to be not only silly, or wasteful, but unfair.  Why get to the endgame if you can't play the endgame?<br>
<br>
The reservation system was set up when level 46-50 was the endgame.  Dragons and the planes.  Those rules have extended beyond kunark, and beyond the level 50 level cap.  They have not extended into Velious.  <br>
<br>
The question now is are those rules going to extend beyond the upgrade to the old world planes.<br>
<br>
I do not think that the rules created for a world where the level cap was fifty should apply anymore. Yes, keep the reservation system, but we must allow for intervention.  There is no reason why we can't balance the competing interests.<br>
<br>
Proposed rule:  The raiders next in line to an old world planar raid have a right of first refusal to kill the <br>
boss(es) of that plane.  It attaches at the start of the previous raid.  However, if that right is waived, the intervenors may attempt to kill the boss.  The right is non-assignable.<br>
<br>
It is a delicate and ephemeral right.  It attaches at the beginning of the previous raid.  Intent to preserve the right may be noticed in the post announcing the raid.  That will be suffcient to prevent a waiver.  <br>
<br>
To obtain a waiver, the subsequent raid leader, or one of his/her designated agents, must give it.  Designated agents must be posted in the post announcing the raid.<br>
<br>
Now there are some problems with this rule.  <br>
<br>
Q:  Some raiders a raid or two down may be able to kill the boss.  Is this fair to them?<br>
<br>
A:  They too could petition for an intervention.<br>
<br>
Q:  Some raiders may sell their wiaver to the highest bidder.  <br>
<br>
A:  Crass, yes, but so what?  But if it offends some, and it certainly might, then the rule could state that the waiver cannot be auctioned.<br>
<br>
Q:  What if people who have no realistic chance of taking out the boss refuse to waive?<br>
<br>
A:  There is always that chance.  Let them commit mass suicide.  You can petition the next group of raiders, and the next group, until you find someone reasonable.  Most of us are.<br>
<br>
I do not like adding rules or modifying them.  Prticularly useless rules.  Unnecessary prolix to a set of rules is an evil to be eshewed.  But the circumstances now require change.  This is the best solution I can think of to this problem.  I thank you all for the time you spent reading this post. <p>Chants Evensong
